'''Kirishimamine Shrine''' (きりしまみねじんじゃ) is a {{ill|lt=Shinto shrine|Q845945|qid=Q845945|1=Shinto shrine}} in Hosono, {{ill|lt=Kobayashi|Q861283|qid=Q861283|1=Kobayashi, Miyazaki}}, {{ill|lt=Miyazaki Prefecture|Q130300|qid=Q130300|1=Miyazaki Prefecture}}. It is a candidate shrine for an {{ill|lt=Engishiki-listed shrine|Q11064932|qid=Q11064932|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō}}, and its former rank was {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=kensha|1=Ken-sha|qid=Q90139226}}.

=== Enshrined deities ===
* {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Ninigi no Mikoto|1=UNKNOWN}} and {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Konohanasakuya-hime no Mikoto|1=UNKNOWN}}<ref name="小林市史3">Kobayashi City History, Vol.3, pp.1095-1097</ref>
* {{ill|lt=Hikohohodemi no Mikoto|UNKNOWN|lt=Hikohohodemi no Mikoto}} and {{ill|UNKNOWN|qid=Q2329261|lt=Toyotama-hime no Mikoto|1=Toyotama-hime}}<ref name="小林市史3"/>
* {{ill|lt=Ugayafukiaezu|Q1373935|qid=Q1373935|lt=Ugayafukiaezu no Mikoto|1=Ugayafukiaezu}} and {{ill|lt=Tamayoribime (Hyuga mythology)|Q3082751|qid=Q3082751|lt=Tamayori-hime no Mikoto|1=Tamayori-hime (mother of Jimmu)}}<ref name="小林市史3"/>
Ninigi, Hikohohodemi, and Ugayafukiaezu are called the {{ill|lt=Three Generations of Hyuga|Q56347075|qid=Q56347075|1=Three generations of Hyuga}}, ancestors of the {{ill|lt=Imperial Household|Q909452|qid=Q909452|1=Imperial House of Japan}}, and the other three are their consorts.

=== Origin ===
[[Image:Kirishimamine Jinja Sando.jpg|thumb|270px|Approach]]{{出典の明記| date = 2022年2月| section = 1}}
The founding date is unknown, though tradition places it around the mid-6th century. It is regarded as a shrine deeply connected with the descent of the heavenly grandson ({{ill|lt=Tenson kōrin|Q1084733|qid=Q1084733|1=Tenson kōrin}}) and the {{ill|lt=Three Generations of Hyuga|Q56347075|qid=Q56347075|1=Three generations of Hyuga}}{{要出典|date=2022年2月}}.

According to shrine tradition, the "Kirishimamine deity" in the entry for August 1, {{ill|lt=837|Q25093|qid=Q25093|1=837}} ({{ill|lt=Jowa (Japan)|Q1075605|qid=Q1075605|lt=Jōwa|1=Jōwa (Heian period)}} 4) of the ''{{ill|lt=Shoku Nihon Kōki|Q1041301|qid=Q1041301|1=Shoku Nihon Kōki}}'' - where Miyazaki's Tonō, Tsuma, Eda, and Kirishimamine deities were granted status as official shrines - refers to this shrine<ref name=":0">{{Cite book|和書 |title=Miyazaki Prefecture Shrine Records |date=1988-09-30|year=1988|publisher=Miyazaki Prefecture Shrine Office}}</ref>{{要出典|date=2022年2月}}.

In ''{{ill|lt=Nihon Sandai Jitsuroku|Q1052981|qid=Q1052981|1=Nihon Sandai Jitsuroku}}'', it is stated that in {{ill|lt=858|Q30371|qid=Q30371|1=858}} ({{ill|lt=Ten'an (Japan)|Q1075611|qid=Q1075611|lt=Ten'an|1=Ten'an}} 2), it was promoted to Junior Fourth Rank Lower<ref name="小林市史3"/>.

There is also a theory identifying this shrine with "Kirishima Shrine" in the ''{{ill|lt=Engishiki Jinmyocho|Q11064932|qid=Q11064932|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō}}'' for Morokata District, Hyuga Province (thus a {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=candidate for Engishiki shrine|1=UNKNOWN}}){{要出典|date=2022年2月}}.

Originally it was enshrined at "Setao" (Semonto Hill / Setoo), between {{ill|lt=Takachiho Peak|Q3514128|qid=Q3514128|1=Mount Takachiho}} and {{ill|lt=Onachi (Miike)|Q11489346|qid=Q11489346|lt=Hiwa-ga-mine (Miike)|1=Ohachi}}, in present-day {{ill|lt=Takaharu|Q1206617|qid=Q1206617|1=Takaharu, Miyazaki}}, Nishimorokata District, Miyazaki. It was therefore also called '''Setao Gongen''', and its betto temple was said to be Setao-ji<ref name="小林市史3"/>.

Around the Tenkei and Tenryaku eras, priest {{ill|lt=Shoku|Q11491623|qid=Q11491623|1=Shōkū}} is said to have founded four other shrines including Himamori Shrine around the mountain foothills, and together with Kirishimamine Shrine (also called the Central Gongen Shrine of Mt. Kirishima) they were called the {{ill|lt=Kirishima Rokusha Gongen|Q11660872|qid=Q11660872|1=Kirishima Rokusha Gongen}}. During the period of {{ill|lt=shinbutsu shugo|Q2279088|qid=Q2279088|1=Shinbutsu-shūgō}}, {{ill|lt=Dainichi Nyorai|Q239847|qid=Q239847|1=Vairocana}} was enshrined at Setao-ji on the approach, and the shrine came to be called '''Kirishima-san Chuo Rokusho (Rokusha) Gongen''' ('''Kirishimamine Shrine''')<ref name="小林市史3"/>. As the name suggests, it became the center of the {{ill|lt=Kirishima Rokusha Gongen|Q11660872|qid=Q11660872|1=Kirishima Rokusha Gongen}}, and Kirishima worship flourished.

In {{ill|lt=1112|Q19525|qid=Q19525|1=1112}} ({{ill|lt=Tenei|Q1193915|qid=Q1193915|1=Ten'ei}} 3), eruption of {{ill|lt=Karakuni-dake|Q3321904|qid=Q3321904|1=Mount Karakuni}}, and in {{ill|lt=1167|Q19678|qid=Q19678|1=1167}} ({{ill|lt=Nin'an (Japan)|Q3577285|qid=Q3577285|lt=Nin'an|1=Nin'an}} 2), eruption of Ōhata-yama burned shrine buildings, but each time they were rebuilt on the original site. In {{ill|lt=1234|Q5424|qid=Q5424|1=1234}} ({{ill|lt=Bunryaku|Q1194125|qid=Q1194125|1=Bunryaku}} 1), a nearby eruption of {{ill|lt=Onachi (Miike)|Q11489346|qid=Q11489346|lt=Hiwa-ga-mine (Miike)|1=Ohachi}} again burned the shrine, and because a spring called Ama-no-I from this highland site dried up, it was moved near the branch shrine Kiribe Ōji Shrine, and that place was called "Shin-Setao"<ref name="小林市史3"/>.

However, in {{ill|lt=1716|Q6892|qid=Q6892|1=1716}} ({{ill|lt=Kyoho|Q1145048|qid=Q1145048|1=Kyōhō}} 1), eruption of {{ill|lt=Shinmoedake|Q514392|qid=Q514392|1=Shinmoedake}} burned it again. The sacred body was first moved to Imabo Gongen and then to Okahara in Hosono village, but as the "Shin-Setao" site became completely deserted, in {{ill|lt=1729|Q6952|qid=Q6952|1=1729}} (Kyoho 14) shrine buildings were rebuilt on the mid-slope of {{ill|lt=Hinamori-dake|Q10942052|qid=Q10942052|1=Hinamori Dake}} and remained there until early Meiji. That location is still called Tsukiji<ref name=":0" />{{要出典|date=2022年2月}}.

It was ranked as {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=kensha|1=Ken-sha|qid=Q90139226}} in {{ill|lt=1872|Q7753|qid=Q7753|1=1872}} (Meiji 5), and after combining {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Hinamori Shrine|1=UNKNOWN}} (also counted among {{ill|lt=Kirishima Rokusha Gongen|Q11660872|qid=Q11660872|1=Kirishima Rokusha Gongen}}) in {{ill|lt=1873|Q7757|qid=Q7757|1=1873}} (Meiji 6), it was moved to the former site of Hinamori Shrine (present location), where it remains today<ref name="小林市史3"/>.

In ''{{ill|lt=Sangoku Meisho Zue|Q11354726|qid=Q11354726|1=Sangoku meisho zue}}'', a record of famous places in {{ill|lt=Satsuma Domain|Q676187|qid=Q676187|1=Satsuma Domain}}, it is written as "'''Kirishima Dai-gongen-gu'''".

Since ancient times it flourished as a noted shrine worshipped by the clans that ruled this area, including the {{ill|lt=Shimazu clan|Q1061406|qid=Q1061406|1=Shimazu clan}}, {{ill|lt=Ito clan|Q2975280|qid=Q2975280|1=Itō clan}}, and {{ill|lt=Kitahara clan|Q11401254|qid=Q11401254|1=Kitahara clan}}. {{ill|lt=Shimazu Yoshihiro|Q1156288|qid=Q1156288|1=Shimazu Yoshihiro}} is also said to have worshipped here while based at {{ill|lt=Iino Castle|Q11666711|qid=Q11666711|1=Iino Castle}}, and to have donated 100 hyo of rice each year as shrine lands<ref name="小林市史3"/>.

